                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d503">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 462.11Se8/12a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Consul General at London</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_SRP1" type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Skinner</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-03-23T17:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">March 23, 1915, 5 p. m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Endeavor ascertain owner cargo <persName>
                        <hi rend="italic">William P. Frye</hi>
                    </persName>, January 28, and any subsequent change of ownership. Consul
                    Queenstown cabled, “Understand <persName>
                        <hi rend="italic">William P. Frye’s</hi>
                    </persName> cargo owned by Leetham’s of Hull, millers, who might or might not
                    have large army contracts.” Shippers inform Department cargo sold November 16 to
                    S. and T. Trounson, Limited, Redruth, England, but changed hands several times
                    in passage. Report fully, giving any facts suggesting Government interest.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Bryan</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
